No liberating amendment for Tymozhenko by Parliament
The Ukrainian parliament today refused to propose to abolish, as part of an amendment to the Criminal Code, the clause on the basis of which opposition leader Yulia Timoshenko had been sentenced.
The new regulation, which could have paved the way for the liberation of the imprisoned ex-premier minister, was rejected by the MEPs at the second reading of the motion for a reduction in the penalties for economic crimes.
Timoshenko was sentenced to seven years in prison in October for concluding an allegedly negative contract with Russia on the purchase of natural gas.
The verdict is not yet final, and the appeal of the convicted is to be brought to court in December.
Timoshenko himself described the verdict as political revenge of the regime and also in the West the trial raised suspicion of the bias of the court.
The request to remove Section 365, on the basis of which the ex-premier minister was sentenced, from the penal code, was supported by 147 MPs.
226 votes would have been required for its adoption.
