Start of a new crisis era
France and the rest of Europe in the focus of investors.
On Tuesday, a statistical storm low blew through Europe.
The individual countries published their data on their GDP for the third quarter.
The Czech economy stagnated compared to the previous quarter, with Germany and France increasing.
But the bond market is breaking all records today.
Investors are keeping an eye not only on Greece, but also on Spain, France, Austria and other countries.
The statistical offices of the European zone, Germany, the Czech Republic and some other European countries published their preliminary forecasts of economic development in the third quarter.
Germany's GDP was expected to grow by 0.5%, and France by 0.4%.
At the same time, both countries corrected their data for the second quarter in which Germany recorded higher growth than originally expected (growth by 0.3% instead of forecast 0.1%), while France admitted a slight decrease of 0.1% (original data only referred to stagnation).
The Czech economy grew by 1.5 percent in this year's third quarter compared to the previous year.
However, compared to the previous quarter, gross domestic product stagnated and, according to the Statistical Office, the trend towards a slowdown in economic performance was thus confirmed.
So the results are worse than the analysts' predictions.
The main events:
The Czech economy grew by 1.5 percent in this year's third quarter compared to the previous year, but it stagnated compared to the previous quarter.
According to provisional and seasonal data, the German economy grew by 0.5 percent in the third quarter.
In the eurozone as a whole and in the EU, the economy grew by 0.2 percent between July and September compared to the previous quarter, which is in line with analysts' expectations.
The Greek economy shrank by 5.2 percent compared to the previous year.
The 10-year government bond yield climbed to 28.45%.
The yield on Italian and Spanish government bonds rose to their critical limits.
Austria, the Netherlands, France, Belgium and other countries are also beginning to feel problems...
