Travel prices since 1989
Until 1989, there were only five state travel agencies in the then ČSSR: Čedok, sporturist, CKM, recrea and autoturist.
At that time the travel agencies sold mainly only trips to the socialist Eastern Bloc countries, to the West at that time only selected ones were allowed.
And so Czech tourists travelled to the Baltic Sea (to the German Democratic Republic - the GDR), to the Soviet Union (Sochi on the Crimean peninsula on the Black Sea), to Bulgaria and Romania to the Black Sea and to Hungary to the Balaton.
A slight exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when one was also allowed to travel to Yugoslavia, then Yugoslavia took a pro-Western course and therefore the journeys to Yugoslavia were severely restricted.
A great paradox of those socialist times was that not even citizens of the Eastern Bloc (i.e. also Czechoslovaks) were allowed to travel freely within the framework of the socialist countries.
If, for example, a citizen of the ČSSR wanted to travel individually to Poland or even to the Soviet Union, then he needed a so-called invitation letter, otherwise individual trips were not possible.
Even then, the travel agencies offered trips to the West, but then one had to accept huge snakes or stay in the sleeping bag in front of the travel agency, or at least have "good acquaintances" in the travel agency.
Even that was not the way things were going.
The so-called foreign exchange pledge - the condition for a departure to the West - was given only "politically reliable" people - the others were not allowed to travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely exchangeable currency, so it would have been impossible to obtain the necessary funds (Western currency) for a trip to the West without a foreign exchange commitment.
Therefore, the vast majority of Czechs spent their holidays in the country, no wonder that the Czechs bought countless weekend houses and daches - a habit that continues to this day.
The Velvet Revolution of 1989 was followed by a travel revolution of the Czechs.
While a holiday in the GDR or Bulgaria was the measure of all things until 1989, the Czechs spent 4.5 million of their holidays abroad last year in countries around the world.
A huge paradox that one is no longer aware of today is the fact that one could not travel to the most popular holiday country of the Czechs - Croatia until 1989 at all, because it was part of the former Yugoslavia.
Right from the beginning of the 1990s, foreign exchange obligations were abolished in neighbouring Western European countries, which caused a huge wave of short visits, especially to Vienna in Austria and to Germany.
The Czechoslovaks could not get enough of their journeys to the West for a long time, everyone wanted to have been there for at least a few days.
For example, the Czech vacationers slept in the tent in the park while travelling to Paris, because who would have had the money for accommodation in the hotel or in a pension at the time.
A typical feature of trips abroad from Czechs was a trunk packed with canned food, beer and sausage, etc.
Another important milestone was the introduction of the freely exchangeable Czech crown - after decades, our tourists were finally able to purchase the Western currency freely.
Our standard of living and, as a result, the average salaries rose, which led to another important moment in 1997.
Thanks to the increased demand for travel, after 1997 travel agencies began to prepare regularly for travel by charter flights, making air travel incredibly cheaper compared to the past thanks to the possibility to negotiate volume discounts.
By the end of the 1990s, the Czechs, with the exception of the US, had already made moneyless payments with all the world's highly developed countries, making travelling even easier.
Another interesting moment in the history of "post-official" travel came in 2000, when, thanks to the high demand, the first direct charter flight to an exotic country was handled - to Thailand.
Since then, direct charter aircraft with Czech passengers have been flying to far-off sunny countries every year; this year, twelve exotic destinations are flying directly from the Czech Republic.
To the 100 thousand Czechs travel to exotic countries every year!
Another important moment in the epoch that marked our "post-revolutionary" development came in 2008.
On 17 November 2008, the United States lifted the visa requirement for Czech tourists, making our country definitely one of the world's highly developed countries.
In 2008, for the first time, the Czechs spent more than half of their holidays abroad (50.3%) and for the first time in their history, they spent more than CZK 15 thousand per capita on a single holiday, including the costs at the resort.
The Annual General Meeting is to find a new chairman - again a stalemate threatens.
For almost five months, Czech football has no chairman, and the successor of Ivan Hašek at the head of the Czech Football Association (FAČR) will not even be known after the extraordinary general meeting in Nymburk on Thursday.
To date, there has been no agreement on which electoral order should be elected.
And without this, no vote is possible at all on the three potential successors.
Three interested parties want to manage Czech football - Jindřich Rajchl, Miroslav Pelta and Tomáš Paclík.
In June, Hašek resigned from his role, calling on his colleagues to agree and find a strong personality to lead football in the future.
Only - in the era after Hašek the old querels broke out again between the two federation chambers, which cannot agree on a common candidate.
This was clearly evident on 16 September when the new chairman was to be selected.
The delegates of the Annual General Meeting had come to the Volkshaus in the Prague district of Smíchov for nothing, because the negotiations did not lead to any result and it was not only about the election itself.
One could not even agree on who is actually entitled to vote at the full assembly - only the statutory representatives or also the functionaries equipped with a power of attorney.
On this only point, agreement was reached at least in part, to which the recommendation of the Institute for State and Law contributed, whose opinion was that representation on a proxy basis was not acceptable.
However, disputes over the electoral system continue.
Nor did the Executive Committee bring any more clarity into the matter, at whose meetings, whether ordinary or extraordinary, there is in principle nothing else on the agenda at all.
Even if the views on the election changed a few times - the neuralgic point remained the same.
The question is: how should one proceed in the 3rd round to avoid a stalemate situation?
"The issue is whether to proceed in accordance with the Articles of Association or whether a completely different model needs to be found," said Dušan Svoboda, one of the three vice-chairmen of FAČR, who represents professional football in management.
According to the statutory model, in the third round, the candidate who receives the greater percentage support in the Chamber for whom he is running wins.
Moravia is allegedly prepared to respond to the compromise that the candidate who receives the higher number of votes from both chambers wins.
The Czech side, in turn, insists on the condition that the winner receives at least a two-thirds majority in this percentage counting.
"Then the two preliminary rounds no longer have any sense at all, this mode would question the entire bicameral concept," Svoboda understands the objections of the Moravian side, which would be best not to bend the electoral order, but to choose according to the valid statutes.
Surprisingly, Tomáš Paclík agrees with this, even though it appears that the statutory electoral order is most likely to meet Pelta from all candidates.
"My wish is that as much as possible be elected according to the statutes."
"So that no nonsensical alternative options can be devised, as at the last general meeting," declared the owner (of the football club) Victoria Plzeň, who ran for the first time and distinguished himself from Pelta in his statements.
But Pelta remains optimistic.
In his opinion, the new chairman will be known in Nymburk and he believes that the candidates will also work constructively together in the future.
"The possible qualification of the national team for the European Football Championship today would certainly contribute to calming the moods."
"When football first rides on the euphoric wave, the willingness to cooperate is also greater," says Jablonec's official, who has the greatest experience of all three adepts, both at a professional and regional level.
Rajchl is more reserved.
"I hope for an agreement, but unfortunately the situation is ambivalent."
"This is not a matter between the people of Bohemia and Moravia, but there are certain efforts to "justify" the regulations for their own purposes."
"Therefore, a further blocking at the Annual General Meeting is not excluded."
"I hope, however, that common sense will ultimately prevail," said Rajchl.
Only - there is not much time left to agree on all sides.
Some negotiations are supposed to take place directly in Montenegro, but who knows whether the football generality will be complete until the qualifying match.
The charter plane, with which among others Dalibor Kučera and Rajchl were to fly to Podgorice, could not start in the morning in Prague because of a technical disturbance and so one searched feverishly for a substitute variant, as one still brings a part of the executive committee to the location of the Barrage-Hinspiel.
In the end, the meeting at ministerial level, which is supposed to take place on Wednesday, is probably crucial.
Josef Dobeš, Minister of Education, Youth and Physical Education, would have liked to have led the divided parties within the largest sports association in the country to an agreement.
There is a lot at stake: state subsidies, the trustworthiness of Czech football and also the upcoming general meeting of ČSTV, which will point the Czech sport in a new direction after the financial problems of Sazka.
Paclík goes into the struggle for the position of chairman because he does not see a suitable candidate
If Tomáš Paclík, the head of the Pilsner footballers, could have made up a strong candidate before the extraordinary general meeting, who would have fulfilled all his ideas about the new chairman of the football association of the Czech Republic (FAČR), he would not have entered the fight for this top position at all.
"If there was a good candidate, I would fight for him and give up the election."
"But in the current situation it was not possible to find such an adept," said Paclík ČTK.
The main reason for Paclík to go to the duel with Miroslav Pelta and Jindřich Rajchl is to prevent the alleged favourite of the election, Pelta, from getting to the head of the FAČR.
Paclík also stresses that, in the event of his victory, he intends to serve as Chairman for only one year, i.e. until 2013, until the date of the Annual General Meeting.
