21er Haus in Vienna
The Moved Pavilion
By Ingeborg Wiensowski
An architectural history with ups, downs and happy endings: The Austrian World Exhibition Pavilion of Brussels won prizes in 1958, became a museum in Vienna, stood empty and disappeared.
Now it is reopened as an exhibition house.
If modern post-war architecture is enthralled by clear forms, glass halls, bold swings and new building materials typical of the belief in technical progress, then the Austrian pavilion of the architect Karl Schwanzer is a striking and famous example of the Brüssler World Exhibition 1958.
At that time, Schwecker's pavilion received the Grand Prix d'Architecture for its light and floating steel-glass construction.
The building is still considered a milestone of contemporary architecture.
He made the architect so famous that he also built the pavilion at the next World Exhibition in Austria.
With his legendary BMW four-cylinder house plus bowl-like annex in Munich, he finally became internationally famous in 1973.
After the World Exhibition in the Swiss Garden, the pavilion, which was planned as a temporary exhibition building, was set up by the Vienna Südbahnhof, rebuilt and opened in 1962 a museum of the 20th century - the "20er Haus" was called it.
However, the building was neither spatially nor technically suitable as a museum - no walls for hanging art, no good climate.
Nevertheless, it was used until contemporary art was given a new home in Vienna.
Since 2001 the building was empty and came down more and more.
Now the architect Adolf Krischanitz has rebuilt the pavilion, it is now called "21er Haus" and will be used as a museum for contemporary art in the future.
Tuesday evening, the Belvedere Museum, to which the house belongs, opens the first exhibition there - a stroke of luck in every respect.
Agnes Husslein-Arco, who became the new director of the Austrian Gallery Belvedere in 2007, has completed the new beginning.
Husslein-Arco, an art historian with a considerable career, among other things, in her youth as an ice skater, later at Sotheby's, the Guggenheim Museum and as founding director of the Museum der Moderne Salzburg, implemented the conversion strongly among politicians and conservationists, raised public funds and private sponsorship funds and determined the use.
Apart from contemporary art, the works of the sculptor Fritz Wotruba were to be exhibited by the foundation of the same name, a café and a bookshop should be there, and an office building had to be built.
Strict supervision, small budget
For the implementation Krischanitz was then the ideal occupation.
Not only because he had sensitively rebuilt and expanded Joseph Olbrich's Secession in Vienna and won the competition, but because he studied at the Technical University of Vienna with Schwanzer and the pavilion was for him a "unfortunately important place" where he had watched the exhibitions "almost every weekend".
He knew the original design, and he knew the problems of the building, which already lost its generosity and lightness when it was moved to Vienna and its conversion.
There were far greater problems with the current reconstruction: the building was "an energy spin", says Krischanitz.
The window profiles of the glass façade were replaced, glass fibre-reinforced insulating glass was used and the glass roof was replaced by special safety glass.
Cold bridge steel beams have been reinforced or replaced, and asbestos-filled ceilings have been rehabilitated.
Two basements brought space for the new use, a lowered light ditch between house and street ensures the exposure, a bridge leads to the entrance - almost a new building, but still the light tail pavilion.
The original exterior doors have remained, the house is painted in the old red-brown rust protection shade.
And the cinema room is even exactly the same as it used to be.
And all under strict supervision of the monument authority and with a small budget.
"Often a material had to be found that is good and cheap and also liked the monument protection office," says Krischanitz, pointing to a rough ground in the basement.
Despite all the constraints, problems and renovations, the building has remained flexible and light.
It had been difficult with the pavilion "which came from Brussels", Krischanitz recently said, a typical "drop-in-the-city story".
Such an architecture is "always in the wrong place" and still wants to "awaken a real consciousness".
In this case, however, the 21er Haus is not in the wrong place, because a lucky urban development case has occurred: The completely newly planned "Hauptbahnhofsquartier", with office and residential buildings, is being created around the Swiss Garden.
And another stroke of luck might happen: The 21er Haus could get reinforcement from another Krischanitz building, because the collector Francesca von Habsburg bought the Berlin Temporary Kunsthalle, and as you can hear, she is already negotiating with the city for a neighbourly location in the Swiss garden.
