Walls Have Eyes: How Researchers Watch You on Facebook
Before becoming the new face of right-wing extremism in Europe, Anders Behring Breivik was just one of many guys who sent their anti-immigration opinion online.
On Monday, Breivik, who confessed to having committed an amok run in Norway in July, in which 77 people were killed, had his first public hearing in court.
Although Breivik may have acted alone, he is far from being alone in cyberspace: he has spent a lot of time on his attack in front of his computer and chatted with some of the millions of nationalists who support far-right groups on the side of social networks.
After the tragedy of this summer, researchers wanted to find out more about these people.
But how do you find them?
This is easy - you only have to log in to Facebook.
"We found that it wasn't difficult to get to them," says Jamie Bartlett, the lead author of a recent report by the British idea factory DEMOS on digital populism in Europe.
Facebook's hideaway of personal data is so encyclopaedic, Bartlett says, that researchers simply need to use the page's advertising tool to precisely define their desired demographic data with scientific accuracy - as marketers have been doing for years.
Bartlett's team found half a million fans of extreme right-wing groups across Europe and then targeted them with add-ons, but instead of linking to a new band or diet product, the Adds invited users to a survey asking for their educational level, their attitude towards violence and their own future.
Thanks to Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues were able to interview more than 10,000 supporters of 14 highly right-wing parties in 11 European countries – without even having to leave their office once.
"It's a rather new research method," says Bartlett.
Some of the results hardly surprise. Online supporters of right-wing extremist groups are mostly young, male and annoyed about immigration.
But in a kind of surprising twist, "those who combine their online activism with an offline activism are more reasonable, more democratic and less violent than those who stay behind their computer screens."
DEMO's work is just one example of how Facebook becomes a new hot tool in the hands of scientists.
Idea factories, medical researchers and political scientists use the site to study everything, from health issues to social trends such as "likes", text messages and status updates.
With more than 800 million active users adding on average three content per day, Facebook's "Data Supernova" generates a research boom that has increased the number of scientific work with the name of this page in the title by nearly 800% over the last five years.
For some researchers, the beauty of Facebook is the fact that through this page you can study people you usually can't reach with your clipboard on the street.
"If you used to try to question people from the British National Party, it was very difficult to identify them."
"They had to inform the party first, and it would never have allowed them access," says Bartlett.
"On Facebook, it's all gone - you go straight to them."
Others say that the site offers a way to identify and solve social health problems.
A recent study by Dr. Megan Moreno from the University of Wisconsin, Madison, and her colleagues has found that students who discussed their drunkenness on Facebook are significantly more prone to drinking problems than students who were silent about this topic.
Moreno suggests that equivalent students, for example residential consultants, monitor the site and help a student if they post too many status updates.
"You can't solve a problem if you haven't recognized it," said Dimitri Christakis, Moreno's co-author and head of Child Health, Behavior and Development at the Children's Research Institute in Seattle, Washington Post.
"We have found a way to identify vulnerable children who would not have been found otherwise."
