Stories about cheating in school and college exams are widespread.
There have been incidents in which teachers gave their students the exam answers to make sure that they were good at their performance checks.
Mentors who should teach the opposite send a message that lies and cheating are okay.
How much deception do we experience?
Studies show that every day we lie between 10 and 200 times.
Many of these lies, however, are considered a lie of necessity.
Another study shows that strangers lie to each other three times during the first 10 minutes of a meeting.
Recognising lies or "uncovering lies" is one that is important for everyone to learn, both for personal and professional reasons.
Far from a social game, such as Scharaden, in which the goal is to call "Have You!", defiling a deception is a serious field of knowledge based on scientific data collected over the past six decades at prestigious universities that have carried out far-reaching research projects, particularly in the fields of psychology and physiology.
One result of the research is that most of the old myths about lying have been exposed.
Lies look you in the eye.
They don't always stutter, stammer, blush, and blush.
However, it cannot be concluded from this that these liars are difficult to uncover and expose.
A trained liar can penetrate to the truth by learning about the structure of the claim, the fine facial expressions, the questioning and timing.
I have spent several years studying the scientific results of the comprehensive and ever-growing field of defiling, and it is clear that defiling a deception is a modern skill that is easy to learn and helps us to find justice in our complex world, especially when hiring or questioning people or negotiating or managing is one of our own professional responsibilities.
Good liars are very good at appreciating other people, raising their interest and mastering their own emotions, and they intuitively sense how they are perceived by others.
Thanks to research, we know that extroverted people lie more often than introverted people, that men are more often "self-directed" lies than women, whose lies are more "oriented" - as a rule they want to protect the feelings of others - that married people lie to their partners less often than unmarried people (but the lies they tell are usually "fat lies").
We also know that when a person has been exposed as an evildoer, others feel less guilty of lying to that person.
How do you know if someone's lying?
First, by observing this person's normal behavior.
It's called "baselining," the starting position.
It provides a reference point for the subsequent evaluation of changes.
Watch the attitude, the laughter, the voice quality of your subject.
You should know better when someone normally always tripping his foot, so they don't blame him wrongly when he's tripping his foot during a meeting.
Then pay attention to accumulations of conspicuous verbal and nonverbal behaviors.
Think of these accumulations as alarm bells that shrill, not as evidence of decloaking.
People who deceive may freeze when they try to remember their story. Maybe their feet point towards the door or they lean toward the exit, change their position in a significant way or show a "relaxation after the interview", this deep, relaxing exhalation and the change in posture when all the hard questions are over.
Questions often falsely signal that an interview is over just to look for this relaxation after the interview.
Also, take care of the language of your subject.
The slip of Scott Peterson is famous when he used the past form when he claimed that his killed wife was still alive and triggered a national search for her.
Disappointing people can also use a distance language: "I had no sexual relationship with this woman... Miss Lewinsky" or if you repeat a tricky question in the whole.
The most common verbal signs are subtle.
Some people use "qualifying language" when they answer a tricky question: "Well... to tell you the truth ... as far as I know ... to the best of my knowledge and conscience."
This makes the answer more perceptive than objective, often causing the alarm bells to shrill.
There's no magic to expose lies, but you can learn skills that make it possible to expose them.
Thanks to these skills, anyone less likely to be the victim of fraud, both in private and professional life.
