Climatic adversity slowed down the economy
In the first year in which Mario López Valdez is in government, unemployment and undeclared work increased in Sinaloa, while foreign investment declined and the economy stagnated.
2011 will be remembered in the economic history of Sinaloa. It is the first year in which Mario López Valdez, who describes himself as the initiator of the change and fuelled great hopes for economic growth, is in government. However, as a result of the climatic adversity, growth cannot be mentioned, but on the contrary, the main economic indicators worsened.
The low temperatures in February not only caused losses of millions in agriculture, but also narrowed the limits to the growth of the state economy and caused a general decline in economic activity of 3.6 percent in the first quarter.This is mainly due to the historic decline in agricultural development by 31.16 percent, which slowed down further economic sectors.
According to a report published by Consejo Mexicano para el Desarrollo Rural Sustentable (Mexican Council for Sustainable Agricultural Development) on the effects of the frost, 582 000 hectares of agricultural land were damaged, 78.03 percent of which were completely destroyed and the remaining 21.07 percent partially destroyed.
The decline in economic activity up to November has led to a steady increase in unemployment in the Mexican state. The Instituto Nacional de Estadística y Geografía observed a rapid increase in unemployment in the first quarter of the year, with 55 053 people in Sinaloa having no employment, equivalent to 4.53% of the labour force. In the second quarter, the unemployment rate rose to 5.28% and from July to September to 6.19%, resulting in 74 000 unemployed in Sinaloa, which is 18 969 more than in the first quarter.
Lower liquidity
The unemployment in Sinaloa in the year goes back to several factors. The economist Gerardo López Cervantes, Dean of the Faculty of Economics and Social Sciences of the University of Autónoma (UAS), comments, the politics of public institutions indirectly explain the growing unemployment.
"What we are seeing at the moment is an increase in unemployment, which has to do with several factors. Among other things, liquidity losses in the market due to the cuts in funds by the legislation adopted to combat money laundering in Congress, because for those who illegally accumulate dollars, it is not easy to let them work for themselves, invest them or use them for anything else," he said.
Migration stopped
López Cervantes pointed out that growing unemployment is also a demographic factor.
"The number of people who leave the country looking for work abroad, especially in the United States, has declined, partly because of the problems of entry and partly because it is difficult to find work there too. These people stay here looking for work here, which causes unemployment to rise," he says.
undeclared work
The analysis of the labour market in Sinaloa is even more serious if one takes into account the high proportion of undeclared work, which, according to INEGI, comprises 60.38 percent of those employed in the country who work without paying into the social security funds.
Unemployment and undeclared work come from low wages, the lowest in all of Mexico, according to the statistics of the Instituto Mexicano del Seguro Social (Mexican Social Security Institute) and the Secretaría del Trabajo y Previsión Social (Government Office for Labour and Social Welfare in Mexico).
The average monthly income of employees in Sinaloa was by September 5352 pesos, which is much less than the national average, which is 7375 pesos.
Decrease in FDI
In addition to reducing economic activity and increasing unemployment, the largest decline in foreign direct investment (ADI) in the last ten years is recorded in 2011. According to Secretaría de Economía (State Economic Authority), the ADI amounted to $630,597 between January and June, representing a decline of 87.74 percent compared to the $5 143,312 in the same period in the previous year.
The Secretaría de Desarrollo Económico del Gobierno (Government Agency for Economic Development) for its part has a total investment of 17 280 000 pesos in 2011, mainly from companies in the tertiary sector.
Debts
In the light of the economic crisis, in July the state government applied to the National Congress for a loan of 3,000,000 pesos to be invested in infrastructure projects in the 18 municipalities in order to reactivate the economy. The State Congress approved an amount of 200 600,000 pesos, but no positive impact of debt on any of the economic sectors in the country could be detected by November.
Reactions
For the representatives of entrepreneurship, the first year of government made Mario López Valdé's incapacity for government obvious.
Miguel Loredo López, chairman of the Cámara Nacional de la Industria de la Transformación (National Chamber of Manufacturing Industry in Mexico), argued that in 2011 no efforts were made to harmonise the views of the different sectors, including the state government.
"Economic activity in Sinaloa was really poor this year, and we need to work hard to regain the ground lost this year, and we need to do twice in 2012. The efforts of all, and in particular the progress of the government team, which has already been well coordinated, have not been sufficiently coordinated," he said.
Slow economic development
Loredo López said that events such as the frost at the beginning of the year made the country's economic development more difficult and slowed down.
"The low economic flow is the result of several events, including the frost. One of the most important effects is a slowed economy that is not moving sufficiently to create an economic dynamic that could generate an acceptable flow of processes, products and services. Therefore, we will complete the year well below our expectations," he said.
Redefining calling
Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, president of the Confederación Patronal de la República Mexicana (Mexican Entrepreneurs' Association) in Sinaloa, said that it was necessary to encourage the state to become more dynamic productive.
"In general, we have observed that work has been done. We believe that it is necessary to develop a long-term program to redefine the country's economic vocation and line, because it is important to activate all Sinaloa's material and human resources," he said.
There's a lot to do
The chairman of Coparmex stressed the importance of developing a future perspective that would better guide the government's efforts.
"In general, I would say that the government has achieved good results in various areas. Economic development has progressed, but it is important to develop a long-term programme," he said.
He stressed that the current state power had made progress with the government.
"There are areas where it can be said that the government has acted more comprehensively. What I can say is that work has been done and that the government is aware that there is still a lot of work ahead of it," he said.
