The court approved the transition to digital television in Mexico in 2015
The transition of analogue to digital signals has been one of the most important changes in the world in recent years.
The Supreme Court of Mexico (SCJN) dismissed the constitutional lawsuits filed by the Senate and the House of Representatives against the Presidential Decree, and by virtue of which the switching from analogue to digital signals from 2021 to 2015 must be brought forward due to the lack of eight votes required to challenge the law.
A minority of four ministers, including the President of the Supreme Court, Juan Silva Meza, considered that President Felipe Calderón had not exceeded his responsibilities when he issued the legislative decree detailing the switchover to terrestrial digital television.
This resolution rejected the constitutional dispute initiated by the Senate because it did not receive the required qualified majority of eight votes so that the court could decide on the constitutionality or non-constitutionality. Thus, the law remains in force.
The project for the lawsuit, prepared by Minister Olga Sánchez Cordero, proposed that the decree be declared unconstitutional, since the regulations relating to radio and television are the responsibility of the Comisión Federal de Telecomunicaciones (Cofetel) (Federal Commission for Telecommunications in Mexico), which is why the decree would contravene the hierarchical principles and the law reserve.
Only Zaldívar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sánchez Cordero voted in favour of the project.
With this argument, both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies filed constitutional complaints against the Legislative Decree. After acceptance of the lawsuits, Minister Sánchez Cordero no longer applied the Legislative Decree and ceased all activities to establish digital transmission.
The Council of Ministers also rejected the case brought by the Chamber of Deputies without going into the debate on the project, which was also the responsibility of Minister Sánchez Cordero.
In his speech, the Prime Minister stated that he did not agree with the project's arguments, in the sense that the country government should not regulate the measures that the public administration should take under general rules.
"I do not believe that if this were done, the independence of the regulatory body would be affected", she also recalled that the central government is responsible for the planning of strategic policy areas, such as the telecommunications sector, for constitutional reasons, for which it is responsible for state affairs.
The replacement of analogue signals by digital is one of the most important changes that have taken place in recent years all over the world, and it makes better use of the radioelectric spectrum, an increased quality of the signal and more channels.
Postponing the changeover, she said, was a postponement of the benefits of digitalisation, which was a decision in the public interest that had not only technical aspects, "because they encompassed economic, social, political and security aspects."
These matters, she emphasized, "needed the action of the entire system, according to the principle of economic governance by the state, they included a group of features that put the constitution in the hands of the central government."
She recalled that many countries around the world had already implemented the digital transition, through the government, even though they had highly specialised facilities.
It could not be concluded that, by issuing the contested decree of law, the government intervened in the powers of Congress, since the laws adopted by the legislature were respected," she assured.
The possibility of counting the ballot papers individually in Michoacán is being considered
According to PREP, the difference between first and second place in the governor's election is almost 27 percent, with 879 votes out of a total of 6074 not yet counted.
The possibility of single counting the ballot papers this year is a reality in the elections in Michoacán, because according to the data issued by the Programa de Resultados Electorales Preliminares (PREP), the difference between first and second place in the governorial elections is almost 27 percent, with 879 votes out of a total of 6074 not yet counted.
In this spirit, the President of the Consejo General del Instituto Electoral de Michoacán (IEM), María de los Ángeles Llanderal Zaragoza, recalled that just last November 9th the Electoral Office adopted a series of rules to harmonise local rules with federal reforms in electoral matters.
It should be recalled that Michoacán had not adapted his political constitution, electoral law, or electoral justice law to the reforms adopted by Congress, so that they had not entered into force during this round of elections. Governor Leonel Godoy Rangel avoided their publication in the State Gazette within the time limits set for this, arguing that he had no objection to it.
On 9 November, the Supreme Court of Mexico (SCJN) ruled on the constitutional action filed by the local legislature and assessed the State Commissioner's vote on the constitutional reforms as "invalid and illegal", as he did not have the right to "decide or veto".
María de los Ángeles Llanderal, in an interview on the possibility of individual counting of votes, explained that, thanks to the adoption of the guidelines by the Consejo General del IEM, there is now the possibility that the local electoral authority can count the ballot papers in part or in full.
Thus, under the following conditions, the votes contained in one or more electoral packages may be partially counted.The results in the minutes do not agree; the minutes of the counting and calculation of votes are not available on file or are not in the possession of the chairman of the election committee or there are obvious errors or amendments in the minutes.
In addition, the total count of the fully completed ballot papers can be made if there is a difference between the alleged winner and the winner in second place, which is equal to or less than one percent, provided that at the beginning of the meeting there is an explicit request from the party or coalition chairman, who is the second of the candidates mentioned above.
The vote count may also be made in its entirety if, after completion of the ordinary calculation, it is established that the difference between the alleged winner and the candidate in second place is equal to or less than one percent, provided that an explicit application is made by a representative of the party whose candidate has become second. In this case, the election packages which have been suspended from a partial count would be excluded.
It is worth noting that the elections in Morelia are in the same situation where, according to PREP, the difference between first and second place is almost 0.16%, although the votes of 129 out of a total of 923 electoral protocols have not yet been counted.
