Yes, the production sent us videos from several groups and we liked this band the best. Therefore, we are curious to see what Las Robertas can offer live. This will be exciting.
Why do you always change the lyrics of Yellow Ledbetter when you play live?
This is a question for Ed (Eddie Vedder), I have no idea.
He sings it, and I think he sings the first thing he can think of.
Who were you influenced by as a bass player?
From so many+
The first to come to my mind are Geezer Butler, John Entwistle, C.J. Ramone, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukowski...
There are so many that I could talk all afternoon about the bassists I like.
How did Pearl Jam manage to keep the grunge alive, even though it is no longer a fad?
I don't think we all feel very attached to the word grunge.
When I think about it, I remember the bands I mentioned before, such as Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana and all the others that came up at the same time. If they are still important today, I think it’s great, because it’s worth listening to this music and bands like Mudhoney are making better music now than ever before.
At first her music was darker, now it is more positive.
Why?
This is interesting, because I think there are a few songs on the new album that might seem a little lighthearted, but there are other songs like The End or Just Breathe that are classified as very dark songs, although they also have something positive in themselves.
The tears came to both of them when I heard Ed playing them. They are very dark songs.
I think when you get older and something sad happens in your life - for example when you lose a family member or a friend - that influences your artistic creation and your music and these two songs clearly embody this for me.
But I also think that you can be a happy person and still make dark music.
