Colom guarantees the delivery of Portillos to the United States
The President of Guatemala, Álvaro Colom, announced this Tuesday that he would allow former Governor Alfonso Portillo to be extradited so that he would be responsible in the United States for the US $70 million money laundering conspiracy.
Thus the trial of the US application for extradition of Portillo ends, so that it can be brought to justice there.
In a press conference, Colom confirmed that his decision was based on the independence of judicial authority and government, taking into account that a ruling court had already ordered extradition.
He stressed that he had not interfered with court decisions during his government and had accepted all extradition requests that he was informed of.
Besides Portillo, Sergio Ruano Marroquín is extradited for murder and assault, Edgar Estrada Morales and Víctor Estrada Paredes, both for drug trafficking.
Colom's action is an act of government which takes place when all judicial and constitutional bodies are exhausted to condemn the former President of the State (2000-2004).
According to the decisions of the Fifth Criminal Court and the Constitutional Court of Guatemala, Portillo must be extradited when his legal situation is clarified in Guatemale and his human rights are guaranteed.
Portillo was acquitted for embezzling 120 million Quetzales in the Ministry of Defense during his reign. This trial was preceded by extradition, but the minister objected and revived the case.
Trinijove has helped 6000 young people threatened with social exclusion
The organisation was set up to avoid the marginalisation of young people without vocational training.
The first 25 years of life of the social assistance organisation Trinijove have led to important results: in this quarter century, 6000 young people threatened with social exclusion were supported in order to find a way out of their difficult situation.
In addition, there are over a hundred jobs created for this social group.
On the occasion of the anniversary, an event was held yesterday in the former factory buildings of Fabra i Coats, in which more than 300 people participated.
Trinijove was founded in 1986 in the district of Trinitat Vella with the aim of helping young people with low levels of education, without work, with drug problems at risk of marginality.
At yesterday's celebration in Sant Andreu, many responsible bodies and institutions took part in the association's work over the past 25 years.
The participation of political representatives of different directions during election campaigns proved the impartiality of Trinijove's work.
Besides the president of the Generalitat (Parliament of the Autonomous Region of Catalonia), Artur Mas, and his predecessor Jordi Pujol participated in the celebrations of the former Socialist Minister of Education Ernest Maragall and the former mayor and currently left-green city councillor Ricard Goma.
The large hall of Fabra i Coats was also visited by the current Catalan Minister of Social Affairs and Family Affairs, Josep Lluís Cleries, and Jaume Lanaspa, Director General of the Social Works of La Caixa Savings Bank.
Mas stressed that Trinijove was born in very difficult times and that today's times are no less complicated, but he added that the work that has been done so far is "a good basis".
For the President of the Generalitat, Trinijove is a model that knows how to fight against difficult circumstances and gives hope to people in trouble.
"The economic crisis is nothing new for the association and the work it does," he explained.
Occupied house, where huge parties were held, was cleared
The owners had occupied 11 of the 13 apartments in the building on Balmes No. 51 (Barcelona).
The twelve squatters left the building yesterday afternoon without any resistance.
Everything points to the fact that the nightmares of the neighbors of house No. 51 on the street Balmes have found an end.
Twelve people voluntarily left the building, which they had illegally occupied and in which they had organized huge festivals, which had driven the neighborhood to despair. The evacuation took place by judicial order without police intervention.
After the eviction, the door lock was replaced to avoid a similar situation.
"From now on, access will be controlled," confirmed the house administrator.
The squatters, who occupied 11 of the 13 apartments of the building - the rest were inhabited - took with them the entire electrical system and part of the water supply. Moreover, they had painted the walls and left behind all kinds of garbage, especially cans of alcoholic beverages.
On the three lower floors huge parties were celebrated, which lasted up to two days and drove the tenants to despair.
Next to the building is a discotheque, Balmes 51, which also suffered damage from it.
Her owner, Maria Pantinat, explained to Europa Press that her business had declined by 80% since the beginning of the occupation.
The owner of the discotheque pointed out that the squatters made their unfair competition because they sold the drinks to three euros, while they cost 10 euros in the discotheque.
In addition, the owner of the leisure place had been reported by the neighbors for disturbance of peace, while according to her statement the noise did not originate from the visitors of the disco, but from the squatters and in particular from the guests of the festivals, which were organized there, and which according to the statements of the angry neighbors in recent weeks became more and longer.
The discotheque's manager explained that the harassment had been so severe that she agreed with the owner of the building that she did not have to pay rent for the last nine months.
The Guardia Urbana (urban police) also confirmed that she had received more complaints from her neighbours in recent weeks.
Last week, the chairman of the PP (Partido Popular - People's Party) in the Barcelona City Council, Alberto Fernández Díaz, demanded that the building be removed immediately and that the problems of civil coexistence and the decline of the district be dealt with.
He explained that only one floor of the building had been occupied before the summer, but that the squatters had penetrated all the floors of the building and almost all the apartments in recent months. In some of them there had even been theft.
In this sense, he added that "it is necessary to put an end to impunity and to take action against the anti-social acts in the building."
Yesterday another building in the Nou Barris district was cleared by the Catalan police.
At 3:30 p.m., the police approached Montral No. 35 after receiving a call from a neighbor who had observed four people entering the building.
The four were immediately arrested.
