But this policy has rarely been analysed from an economic point of view.
There is a broad consensus on this issue between the right and the left.
On the right hand side, the tone of Jacques Chirac, who declared in 1976 that "900,000 unemployed, including over 2 million immigrated workers, should not be a problem for a country", on the left hand side by Michel Rocard, who had stated in 1990 that "France could not absorb all of the world's poverty".
The only difference is the degree of generosity
The fear of the invasion of the national soil by hordes of Polish plumbers was divided in 2005 from both right and left.
Both camps perceived immigrants as a burden on the economy and French society.
The only difference is the degree of generosity that one is willing to admit to immigrants.
Francois Hollande confines himself in his programme to banalities, which point out that development in partnership allows us to solve our "migration problems".
This idea of immigration as a burden, as a problem, may affect the elections, but it is economically costly.
As economists Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron point out in a recent work summarising the latest findings on immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 p.), there is a broad consensus among specialists on the positive impact of the flood of immigrants on economic growth, wages and jobs in the immigration countries.
Limiting immigration would reduce growth and damage the labour market situation.
The fears about the influence of migrants are based on the idea that they are threatening to substitute the local workers, especially the less qualified ones, by exerting pressure on their wages.
However, experience shows that immigrants are, in fact, much more complementary than domestic wage-earners, as they are mainly engaged in occupations in sectors that are unencumbered in terms of employment.
The low-skilled immigrants work in sectors that do not attract local wage earners, the more skilled among immigrants work in dynamic sectors where education is not aligned with labour supply.
Positive wage effect
Just as a surgeon would have difficulty working in a country where there is a lack of anaesthesiologists, this complementarity also has a positive effect on wages and the domestic labour market between natives and migrants.
Giovanni Peri has calculated in this way that a 1% increase in the flood of immigrants would result in a related, long-term increase in real wages between 0.6% and 0.9%.
And this without taking into account the fact that the diversity of ideas introduced by immigrants and economic growth is beneficial (high proportion of naturalized immigrants among American Nobel laureates; Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay and Yahoo were founded by immigrants).
Migrants also contribute net to social systems, on average around 1% of the total budget in European countries.
The World Labour Organisation estimates, for example, that a person immigrating to Germany at the age of 30 will, on average, contribute a net contribution (revenue minus expenditure) of around 150,000 euros to the public budget over his or her lifetime.
Nicolas Sarkozy wished to bring about the missing intersections "with the teeth" at the beginning of his mandate.
However, these said teeth, which were supposed to deter immigrants, achieved exactly the opposite effect.
