Nord Stream, new gateway to Russian gas in Europe
The Nord Stream gas pipeline, which runs on the seabed of the Baltic Sea and connects Western Europe directly with Russia, has been put into operation.
It is intended to supply gas for an equivalent of 30 million households.
The Russian gas giant Gazprom wanted to celebrate this event with splendor and Gloria.
More than 500 invited guests, including four heads of state and government, attended the inauguration of the new Nord Stream gas pipeline, which connects Russia and Germany directly under sea level, last Tuesday on the Baltic coast under orchestral sound system and gourmet buffet.
German Chancellor Angelika Merkel, Russian President Dmitri Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his Dutch counterpart Mark Rutte symbolically turned the valve's steering wheel, which transports the Russian gas to the western European network.
The new gas pipeline is expected to deliver 27.5 billion cubic metres of additional Russian gas per year to Western Europe through a first pipeline of 1,224 km in length connecting the Saint Petersburg region with Mecklenburg-Vorpommern.
A second pipeline, which allows a total supply of 55 billion cubic metres of gas - the equivalent of the French total consumption - will be completed by the end of 2012.
And you already let the eventuality of building a third line sound on your own track.
For Gazprom, the timely and precise completion of this enormous building looks like a victory.
The project was highly controversial in Poland and the Baltic States.
The Nord-Stream pipeline will allow direct gas delivery to Germany, avoiding any path through third countries (Poland or Ukraine) by land.
For this reason, these two countries are losing some of their power: it is now more difficult for them to exert pressure on Russia by threatening to close access to Western European markets.
Warsaw, most engaged in the debate, was not afraid to compare the Nord-Stream pipeline with a "new German-as well asite pact" in connection with the alliance between Hitler and Stalin for the occupation of Poland in 1939.
This means that the subject is politically sensitive.
Western Europe has gained even greater security of supply by supporting this Russian project.
This, however, at the expense of a reduction in European energy, as the project has struck a breach between Western and Eastern Europeans.
In less than five years, Russia has managed to enforce its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich Western countries, which have strong gas consumption and whose gas deposits are running out.
"This gas pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, it is a new artery that connects us in an organic way", confirmed François Fillon at the inauguration of the gas pipeline, pointing out the extent to which the large gas contracts are also important from the political and economic side.
All this explains the broad smile of the numerous Gazprom managers represented in Lubmin regarding gas supply.
The construction of this gas pipeline is also an outstanding technology.
The underwater line is made of steel with concrete coating, which is intended to protect it from ship anchors.
It rests on the bottom of the sea, at a depth of about 200 m.
During their construction, minefields dating from World War II had to be avoided.
"Some hundreds of mines had to be removed or destroyed as a precaution," Jens Müller, Spokesman of Nord Stream, stated.
In addition, increased measures had to be taken to protect the fauna and flora.
The line is a long line of metal, heavy as 242 Eiffel towers, which is not interrupted by anything over the entire length: neither through valves, nor maintenance stations.
A control platform was planned off the coast of Sweden, but the project managers have refrained from doing so, as the Swedes were not keen to see a Russian state company permanently settling at the level of their coasts.
"In the event of an accident, we close the gas passage in less than one minute," Jens Müller specified.
In the event of a leak, the gas in the gas pipeline escapes into the air.
However, this case is considered unlikely by the designers as the weld seams were estimated to be resistant to one leak per 100,000 years.
State monitoring of the gas pipeline is ensured both by an underwater robot controlled for external observation purposes from a seagoing vessel and by a device circulating inside the gas pipeline.
It has the shape of a cigar, having a diameter of one meter, is inserted into the inside of the pipe and moved by the gas pressure.
After three complete days of movement through the line at a speed of 3 meters per second, the device provides the most accurate information on its arrival about any deformations of the metal.
The gas pipeline was designed to function for fifty years without even having to undergo the slightest repair.
The gas circulation is easily ensured by pressure.
This is 200 bar at the access point, 100 bar at the exit point.
Five societies have combined their forces to realize this project.
However, the management remains in the hands of Gazprom, which holds 51% of the shares.
In addition, the German companies E. ON and BASF are affiliated (15.5%), as are the Dutch Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (both 9%).
These five companies have formed a group of companies called Nord Stream, which is responsible for the construction and operation of the gas pipeline.
It is based in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then rented out the entire capacity of its gas transport to this company, on a renewable twenty-year contract.
"Gazprom will pay for the total capacity, no matter how large the real volume of gas transported will be," Jens Müller specified.
The financing of gas pipeline construction was secured by 30% of shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
Total labour costs should be EUR 7.4 billion for both pipelines.
For GDF Suez, for example, the investment amounted to 240 million.
However, minority shareholders are prepared to recover their expenses, as Gazprom alone bears the liability risk.
The gas pipeline emerges from the Baltic Sea on a sandy coastal stretch of pine forest near Lubmin.
The 4.5 meter high valves form the gas outlet gate.
Sensors measure pressure, temperature and other parameters of the incoming gas before it is transferred to the German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, this terminal has been supplied with one million cubic meters of Russian gas per passing hour.
With full capacity, this would be 3 million cubic metres per hour and 6 million in 2012.
