Why does the unemployment rate of disabled workers remain at such a high level?
About 19% of disabled people are looking for a job.
Today begins the "15th week of work for the disabled".
Despite a target-oriented public policy introduced in 2005, the unemployment rate for disabled people is always twice as high as the average: 19% against 9% unemployment for the total population.
Disheartening?
"No, according to Éric Blanchet, Director General of the Adapt Association, who organizes the "work week for the disabled".
"The progress made within fifteen years is considerable."
"At that time, the unemployment rate was not twice as high, but three times as high."
"Nevertheless, there is still a lot to do."
However, it must be said that many obstacles remain for disabled unemployed people before they get a job.
It is more common for older people: 37% are older than 50 years (17% on average).
They have a low level of qualification: 80% of them have no Abitur and there are only 10,000 disabled people among the 2.3 million students with higher education.
Finally, long-term unemployment is also very widespread: 53% for the disabled, compared with 38% for the total.
In short, there are so many criteria that make it difficult to re-enter the labour market and that make up the core of the problem, says Christian Grapin, Director General of Tremplin, an association set up in 1992 to help companies recruit disabled workers.
So much for the factual brakes.
Remains the unspoken, the attitudes that are certainly but slowly developing.
A study carried out in April by the Association IMS-Entreprendre for the journal La Cité stated that the managers surveyed had "a weak level of knowledge regarding disabled people", which was "overrepresented" "by persons in wheelchairs, mentally or intellectually disadvantaged".
As a result, private companies with more than 20 employees still have a long way to go to achieve the employment target of 6% disabled workers, which was laid down in a 1987 law.
These latter figures, which date from 2008, refer to a ratio of 2.6%.
"We are now at around 3%," says Pierre Blanc, General Director of Agefiph, the organization responsible for collecting contributions from companies that are not complying with this law.
The proof: The number of "paying" establishments has decreased, as has the sum of the paid-up amounts between 2007 and 2011, from 59,000 to 46,000 (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
"The 2005 Act, which provides for increases in contributions, put a lot of pressure on companies," Pierre Blanc said.
"But this improvement also expresses a real insight, especially among the large groups of companies."
According to the Ministry of Labour, only 59% of workplaces between 20 and 49 employees employ disabled workers, while enterprises with 100 to 199 employees employ 82%.
